cs.CL, cs.AI, cs.LG, cs.IR, cs.NE 

This paper is about improving and interpreting a dual encoder model for response suggestion in dialogue. The main focus is on natural language processing (NLP) and machine learning (ML) techniques, which are typically covered in the cs.CL (Computation and Language) sub-category. The paper also discusses attention mechanisms, regularization losses, and neural networks, which are relevant to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. The use of residual layers and word-level interpretability suggests a connection to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. The paper also evaluates the proposed model on two public datasets, which falls under the cs.IR (Information Retrieval) sub-category. Finally, the use of mutual information and approximation methods suggests a connection to the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category.
